==English==
===Etymology===
From Latin ''[[videlicet]]'' (that is to say, namely), short for ''[[videre]] [[licet]]'' (it is permissible to see, it is allowed to see). The ''z'' is originally not a letter but the usual Middle Latin twirl that was used as a shorthand symbol for the ending -et.

===Adverb===
{{wikipedia}}
'''viz.'''
#(''dated'') [[namely]], as [[follows]], that is to say
#:''There are three simple tenses, '''viz.''' past, present and future.''
#*'''Usage note:''' Used to introduce a list or series.
====Pronunciation====
Usually read out as ''[[namely]]''. Otherwise pronounced as follows:
*IPA: /vɪz/